# PWA & Real-Time Features

## Progressive Web App Architecture

### Service Worker Pipeline

1. `next-pwa` generates Workbox service worker at build time
2. `ServiceWorkerRegistration.tsx` registers `/sw.js` on mount (disabled in dev)
3. `worker/index.js` handles: push notifications (multi-language), periodic sync (8hr schedule refresh), window message relay
4. `InstallBanner.tsx` detects `beforeinstallprompt` event → platform-aware install UX

### Caching Strategies (`pwa.config.js`)

| Asset | Strategy | TTL | Rationale |
|---|---|---|---|
| Google Fonts | CacheFirst | 1 year | Immutable CDN content |
| Static fonts/images | StaleWhileRevalidate | 30 days | Rarely change |
| JS/CSS bundles | StaleWhileRevalidate | 30 days | Versioned by Next.js |
| API GET requests | NetworkFirst | 2 days | Fresh data preferred, cache fallback |
| Next.js `_next/data` | StaleWhileRevalidate | 24 hours | Page data JSON |
| Cross-origin | NetworkFirst | 1 hour | Short-lived external |

**API exclusions**: `/api/auth/*` and `/api/iam/*` are never cached (security-sensitive).

### Push Notifications

- `PushNotification.tsx` manages browser push subscription lifecycle
- Subscribes via `PushManager.subscribe()` with VAPID public key
- Uploads subscription to server via notification service
- Unsubscribes on logout (prevents orphan subscriptions)
- Worker renders notifications with locale-aware title/body (en, ro)

### Offline Fallback

- Document fallback: `/offline` page
- Configured in `next.config.mjs`: `fallbacks: { document: '/offline' }`
- Separate offline pages for root (`/offline`) and MGT (`/mgt/offline`)

## WebSocket — Real-Time Roster Editing

### Architecture

`src/app/mgt/(wfm)/(rosters)/components/websocket-manager/index.tsx` (900+ lines) — manages concurrent roster editing.

### Connection Lifecycle

1. Connect to env-specific WSS URL with JWT as subprotocol
2. Ping/pong keepalive every N seconds
3. On disconnect: cleanup timers, release locks
4. No automatic reconnection implemented — page must be refreshed

### Event Protocol

| Event | Direction | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `ACQUIRE_LOCK` | Client → Server | Lock row for editing (optimistic) |
| `RELEASE_LOCK` | Client → Server | Release row lock |
| `LOCK_ACQUIRED` | Server → Client | Broadcast: row locked by user |
| `LOCK_RELEASED` | Server → Client | Broadcast: row unlocked |
| `VALIDATE_CHANGES` | Client → Server | Server-side validation before save |
| `VALIDATION_RESULT` | Server → Client | Validation pass/fail |
| `PUBLISH_CHANGES` | Client → Server | Commit changes to roster |
| `COUNT_UPDATED` | Server → Client | Pending change count notification |

### Concurrency Model

- **Optimistic row locking**: user clicks row → acquires lock → edits → validates → publishes → releases
- Other users see locked rows as read-only in real-time
- Lock state tracked in Redux `rosterState` slice
- WebSocket URL constants per environment in `src/app/mgt/(wfm)/(rosters)/constants.ts`

## Analytics

- `logGAEvent()` from `@/utils/analytics/` — sends to Google Analytics
- Detects platform via `display-mode: browser` media query: `'web'` vs `'pwa'`
- Different GA measurement IDs per region and environment
